d.read_csv(\"chi1__2__lyst1729241145055.csv\")\ndf.head()","metadata":{},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### Step 2: Check Data Types & Value Counts","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"print(df.dtypes)\nprint(df['age intervals'].value_counts())\nprint(df['Experience intervals'].value_counts())","metadata":{},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### Step 3: Create a Contingency Table","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"ct = pd.crosstab(df['age intervals'], df['Experience intervals'], margins=True)\nprint(ct)","metadata":{},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### Step 4: Perform Chi-Square Test for Independence","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"chi2, p, dof, expected = stats.chi2_contingency(ct)\n\nprint(f\"Chi-Square Statistic: {chi2}\")\nprint(f\"P-value: {p}\")\nprint(f\"Degrees of Freedom: {dof}\")\nprint(\"Expected Frequencies:\\n\", expected)","metadata":{},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### Step 5: Interpret Results","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"if p < 0.05:\n    print(\"Reject the Null Hypothesis: Age and experience intervals are independent.\")\nelse:\n    print(\"Fail to Reject the Null Hypothesis: Age and experience intervals have a relationship.\")\n","metadata":{},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 4. Goodness of Fit Test: Analyzing Sales Distribution\n\n### Problem Statement\nA company wants to check whether the observed sales of chips match the expected distribution.\n\n### Hypotheses:\n- **Null Hypothesis (H₀):** The claimed sales distribution is false.\n- **Alternative Hypothesis (H₁):** The claimed sales distribution is true.\n\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### Step 1: Define Observed and Expected Values","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"expected = [50, 50, 50, 50, 50]\nobserved = [50, 